{"success": true, "message": "Fetched question.", "data": {"showTimer": true, "showAttemptInsight": true, "playSounds": true, "dontShowCorrectAnswerImmediately": false, "_id": "6682bd20ba0e94a3c4025aac", "type": "singleCorrect", "level": 2, "category": null, "approximateTimeRequired": 120, "imageBaseUrl": null, "helperText": null, "source": "", "questionLabels": [], "question": {"text": "Given below are two statements:</p><p>Statement (I) : Oxygen being the first member of group <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn></math>\u00a0exhibits only<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>\u00a0</mo><mo>\u2013</mo><mn>2</mn></math> oxidation state.</p><p>Statement (II) : Down the group <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn></math> stability of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></math>\u00a0oxidation state decreases and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn></math>\u00a0oxidation state increases.</p><p>In the light of the above statements, choose the most appropriate answer from the options given below:", "image": null}, "options": [{"id": "BUOUg", "text": "Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect\u00a0", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "TP5Rx", "text": "Both Statement I and Statement II are correct", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "bNzHV", "text": "Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect", "image": null, "isCorrect": true}, {"id": "zFqQ7", "text": "Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}], "correctValue": null, "solution": {"text": "<p>Statement-I: Oxygen can have oxidation state from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></math> to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></math>, so statement I\u00a0is incorrect</p><p>Statement- II: On moving down the group stability of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></math>\u00a0oxidation state increases whereas stability of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn></math>\u00a0oxidation state decreases down the group, according to inert pair effect.</p><p>The inert-pair effect is\u00a0the tendency of the two electrons in the outermost atomic s-orbital to remain unshared in compounds of post-transition metals.</p><p>So both statements are wrong.</p>", "image": null}, "videoSolution": null, "bucket": "Must Do Ques (JEE Main) - Any Difficulty", "concepts": [], "masterId": "MOGJMPYQ96362426", "subject": "Chemistry", "subjects": ["615d70bd9948bc1b21da2b1f"], "chapters": ["615d6fee2b295b085ab6ebbf"], "topics": [], "previousYearPapers": [{"_id": "65c4c0c01d30997d3436baff", "title": "JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 2)", "isVisible": true}], "numericalLowerLimit": null, "numericalUpperLimit": null, "classes": [], "microConcepts": [], "exams": ["615d76b2c52ffa3c944600df"], "isRemoved": false, "cpyqbSubjects": ["615f0cf69476412f48314dac", "616057040283de43c87e3e16", "61bb58281213731910ea0b71", "6160579d0283de43c87e3e1f", "61964f94a5a526011886801e", "61c055f6e8ce0dc8a5c62d34", "61a8a2cce8ce0dc8a5c62d2e", "6160577e0283de43c87e3e1c", "616057210283de43c87e3e19", "629105adee9e3ae00d63352c", "62962075e7f8e9ac4daeafd8", "629f385f263330a77be9fa7e", "629f39e4ac11b26562e0625c", "61964ff3a5a5260118868022", "64d50c263df7f4a7f3017f70", "66b79b89d4b564dfab4f94d0", "678ea9a09cc79e5f592bdc12", "67fa602f4468eb1307ceb0ae", "6807d350647479b8e869647a"], "cpyqbChapters": ["616024e792b48ffe0c828ffe", "616024e6723fa7f4a4682cb0", "61bb8213f08b791379095d32", "61e7bd72934cc32c8e6dc08d", "61964cb29a6808754d18d8ff", "61c0898cb44d09aaffccb2eb", "616024e35e540b845773a794", "61964caf7edaeada1b170fb3", "616024e6299160c79fc84ccb", "629109df142f7e390707f4fc", "62962119b89321d798767711", "629f39010539a31f746f1097", "616024e4a6c25e36152cb2b2", "629f3a8718c42b5cfc891871", "64eb06ca3118f713ecfef0d